@node Requirements "System Requirements"

@{b}System Requirements@{ub}

LazyMines will run on any Amiga computer with version 2.0 or higher of the OS
(or at least I hope it will). If you have version 2.1 or higher LazyMines will
try to use the language you have selected through Preferences. If you have
version 3.0 or higher LazyMines will try to use lots of colors for the
graphics.

@endnode


@node Installation "Installation"

@{b}Installation@{ub}

To install LazyMines from scratch or to update an old version just run the
installation script.
If you choose to install the MagicWB style icons without having MagicWB
installed you can still get them look nice. For this purpose you need at least
an 8 color WB and you will have to load the correct color palette into the
Palette Preferences. The palette can be found in the misc dir (one for 2.x and
one for 3.x).

@endnode


@node Menu "The Menu"

@{b}The Menu@{ub}

@{u}Game@{uu}
New                 - Start a new game.
Novice              - Set level to novice and start a new game.
Amature             - Set level to amature and start a new game.
Expert              - Set level to expert and start a new game.
Fastest Sweepers... - Show the fastest sweepers.
About...            - Show info about program (i.e. version number and author).
Quit LazyMines      - Quit the program (same effect as pressing the
                      closegadget).

@{u}Settings@{uu}
Warnings      - Make it possible to place warnings.
Auto Mark     - If this is selected the game will mark obvious mines
                automatically.
Safe Openings - With this active you won't hit a mine on your first move.
Save Settings - Save the settings (uses @{"tooltypes" link Tooltypes}).

@endnode


@node Display "The Display"

Depending on the size of the screen you are opening LazyMines on the display
will look different. If the screen is small the timer and the flag counter will
be displayed in the title bar of the window, otherwise you will get nice
digital counters. The counter to the left is the flag counter and the one to
the right is the timer.

@endnode


@node Game "The Game"

I don't think there is any need for an thorough explanation - if you
haven't played any minesweeper game by now you're probably not interested
in playing LazyMines either. All you need to know is this:

Use the left mousebutton to reveal a cell.
Use the right mousebutton to lock an unlocked cell. Pressing the right button
over a locked cell will remove the lock (if you have selected Warnings from the
Settings menu this will place a warning on that cell instead. Press the right
button once more to remove the warning too).
Use both (right and left) mousebuttons to reveal all cells around the cell
you clicked on. If you have Auto Mark activated pressing both buttons will
also make the game place flags on cells that obviously must be a mine.

@endnode


@node Tooltypes "Tooltypes"

The following tooltypes are recognized by LazyMines:

PUBSCREEN=<name of public screen>
Use this to open the window on other public screens than the default one (if
there is no public screen with the given name, the program will try to open its
window on the default public screen).

LEVEL=<Novice | Amature | Expert>
Use this to set the initial level.

WARNINGS, AUTOMARK and SAFEOPEN
These tooltypes are used to activate the menu items in the Settings Menu at
startup.

@endnode


@node History "Version History"

@{b}Version History@{ub}

v1.0 (94-04-21) First public release.
v2.0 (94-08-27) LazyMines will now adjust the display so that it will fit on
                almost any screen.
                Added timer and High Scores.
                Now with three difficulty levels.
                Added Save Settings menuitem in the Settings menu.
                Localized LazyMines.
                Improved graphics.
v2.1 (94-12-03) Saves ten high scores for each difficulty level.
                Now with installation script for Commodore's Installer.

@endnode


